column49: The sequence of activities were designed to connect language and content objectives to the work of the unit of study and essential questions. ("How can labeling help me in my writing?" "How can I distinguish between text and illustration"?)
column53: Classroom interaction among the teacher and individual students ae highly respectful, refleecting genuine warmth and caring and sensitivity to students as individuals. The teacher exhibits good classroom management skills. The teacher praises students by saying, "Good job", "Thats great."
column57: The lesson was well planned and prepared using your extensive knowledge of the content area and included some of the components required. The lesson plan incorporated the mini-lesson, guided practice, independent practice, assessment, group practice, summary. The teacher circulated during small-group and/or independent work, offering suggestions to students. The teacher  used specifically formulated questions to elicit evidence of student understanding. The teacher reviewed students work and conferenced with them as the teacher circulated around the classroom.
column59: Teacher analyzes and uses assessment/student work data to identify next steps in instruction.

column49: She is very creative and enthusiastic, but she needs more structure and organization of ideas and concepts. She also is having difficulty connecting to the Ss core content classes. She is, however, working on these elements.The candidate is humble and recognizes her limitations and wants to learn and grow, but she is severely lacking in grammatical understanding which clearly presents a problem for an ESL teacher.
column53: Again, the candidate is aware of some disruptive behavior and is trying to come up with solutions to the problems of attendance and certain Ss dominating the class.

column49: The candidate is struggling with connecting her lessons to core content and making sure that the lessons are beneficial. She needs to more precise, structured and organized in her planning of the lessons, but she is consciously working on this. We also discussed some lack in English grammar comprehension, but I think that she is actively seeking to improve in this area as well.
column53: The candidate is having some difficulty with classroom management and keeping the class on task, however it has more to do with the shared environment of the co-teacher than her skill in this domain. I have seen the candidate in a classroom where she was alone and she has good, solid classroom manangement practices in place, so we are brainstorming if there are any creative ways that she can still keep her class on track even in an environment that she cannot control.
column57: The students love this candidate. She has positive and contagious enthusiasm. She also has an entering Arabic speaking student and she is still able to incite participation from her even though it is quite difficult.

column53: In general, Christina has a good grasp on classroom procedures and interacts well with her students. She might need help dealing with on particular student.
column57: During my visit, students were duly engaged with age and level appropriate materials. Most students responded to her prompts and questions. Interaction conveyed a sense of excitement on the part of students and their teacher.
column59: Christina reflected on her lesson during our post-observation conference, explained where she felt she needed improvement and accepted suggestions for improvement. She also identified areas where she had performed as expected.

column53: Some work might be necessary on transitioning. In general, the class was well managed, and there was a sense that students had internalized a set of routines although they might night some work in some areas.
column57: Students were appropriately engaged, especially during the oral review of the previous lesson. Some work is needed on monitoring the most challenged students and helping them improve their production.
column59: Heather had no trouble identifying areas that needed improvement, as well as those in which she excelled.

column49: Content objective was appropriately challenging and well supported by different types of learning activities. Differentiation was provided as needed.
column53: This lesson was a model of mutual respect between students as well as between students and the teacher. The teacher created a positive learning environment while at the same time reinforcing good student behavior.
column57: Learning activities were well supported by appropriate scaffolding. Student worksheets were well-designed to elicit feedback both from the instructor and from students peers.
column59: The teacher thoughtfully analyzes each component of the lesson. In addition, he attempts to improve his planning by drawing on latest pedagogical theories and best practices. He is very open to trying new ideas and alternative approaches.

column49: Language objective was clearly defined and well integrated with the content objective. Differentiation was built into the lesson plan as well as provided on-the-spot to accommodate students' needs during an activity.
column53: The teacher conveys genuine caring for the students, while gently but firmly maintaining order and discipline. The students respond well to the teacher's encouraging attitude by taking risks with the language. The teacher is very responsive to individual student needs.
column57: Activities were well supported by appropriate scaffolding. The teacher engaged most of the students in the class discussion using various methods, including encouraging students to bring their own cultural associations to the discussion.
column59: The teacher carefully reflected on this lesson's strengths and weaknesses and made suggestions for future improvements. I was also pleased to see the progress this Fellow has made in both teaching skill and self-reflection since last semester.

column49: The teacher incorporated solid pedagogical practices into all aspects of the lesson plan; however, some beginning ELLs could have benefitted from additional questioning to ensure comprehensibility. In addition, the lesson activity, a debate, needed questions with richer content to further engage all students.
column53: The teacher creates a lively, high-energy classroom environment that promotes participation and peer-to-peer support. Many of the teacher's classroom management techniques seem second nature both to her and to her students, who are extremely well-behaved.
column57: The teacher asked students to elaborate on their answers in a way that pushed both content and thinking skills. At the same time, as noted above in Domain 1, lower-level ELLs could have benefitted from additional questioning to promote engagement in the task and assess their learning.
column59: The teacher was able to honestly assess the strengths and weaknesses of this lesson. She took an active role in devising strategies for revising the activities for subsequent lessons.
